04359nam a22006135i 9780822384151DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20032002ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223841517 a10.1515/97808223841512doi  a(DE-B1597)554431  a(OCoLC)1226679150  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aMED0350002bisacsh04a362.1961362231 aMol, Annemarie, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Body Multiple :bOntology in Medical Practice /cAnnemarie Mol; E. Roy Weintraub, Barbara Herrnstein Smith. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2003] 4cÂ©2002  a1 online resource (216 p.) :b4 b&w photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aScience and Cultural Theory00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1. Doing Disease -- t2. Different Atheroscleroses -- t3. Coordination -- t4. Distribution -- t5. Inclusion -- t6. Doing Theory -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Body Multiple is an extraordinary ethnography of an ordinary disease. Drawing on fieldwork in a Dutch university hospital, Annemarie Mol looks at the day-to-day diagnosis and treatment of atherosclerosis. A patient information leaflet might describe atherosclerosis as the gradual obstruction of the arteries, but in hospital practice this one medical condition appears to be many other things. From one moment, place, apparatus, specialty, or treatment, to the next, a slightly different "atherosclerosis" is being discussed, measured, observed, or stripped away. This multiplicity does not imply fragmentation; instead, the disease is made to cohere through a range of tactics including transporting forms and files, making images, holding case conferences, and conducting doctor-patient conversations.The Body Multiple juxtaposes two distinct texts. Alongside Mol's analysis of her ethnographic material-interviews with doctors and patients and observations of medical examinations, consultations, and operations-runs a parallel text in which she reflects on the relevant literature. Mol draws on medical anthropology, sociology, feminist theory, philosophy, and science and technology studies to reframe such issues as the disease-illness distinction, subject-object relations, boundaries, difference, situatedness, and ontology. In dialogue with one another, Mol's two texts meditate on the multiplicity of reality-in-practice.Presenting philosophical reflections on the body and medical practice through vivid storytelling, The Body Multiple will be important to those in medical anthropology, philosophy, and the social study of science, technology, and medicine.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aAtherosclerosiszNetherlands. 0aEthnographic informantszNetherlands. 0aMedical anthropology. 0aMedicinexPhilosophy. 0aOntology. 0aSocial medicine. 7aMEDICAL / Health Care Delivery.2bisacsh1 aSmith, Barbara Herrnstein, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWeintraub, E. Roy, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822384151zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822384151423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822384151.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles